caption:
Imagine speaking on stage…

And just minutes in, 1/2 the crowd gets up and walks out of the venue.

That’s exactly what happened to me back in 2018.

I had the honor of opening for Les Brown…

A real O.G. and legend of the personal development game.

I’d listened to his speeches for years on YouTube.

And there I was, in my own backyard of Tampa, FL.

With friends and my entire team in the audience…

I had a chance to share the stage with him.

At the last minute, I was asked if I was ok with Les going before me. 

Out of respect for Les, of course I agreed.

But in my mind I was thinking…

Are you kidding me? Les Brown is gonna open for me!? Let’s f*cking go.”

I was ready. 

I was prepared. 

I had an opportunity and it was time to seize the moment.

About 5 minutes and 2 f-bombs into my talk…

About a dozen people got up and left.

Then another dozen.

And another.

And, I think you get the point.

Not even 10 minutes in, legit 1/2 the audience had walked out.

In that moment, I realized the mistake I had made.

This wasn’t my crowd- it was a mostly Les Brown audience.

Older, traditional, African American, Christian…

And there I was, speaking with blunt force honesty, dropping F-bombs unapologetically.

Shit.

To say I felt embarrassed was an understatement.

I felt terrible that I put everyone who was there to see me that day in the position where they had to experience that.

My keynote was an hour- but I barely remember any of it.

The words were coming out of my mouth…

But my mind was elsewhere.

As I walked off stage, I remember thinking to myself….

What a huge disappointment that must of been to everyone who paid for a ticket to the event.

I sat in the dressing room for a few minutes in silence.

Mentally preparing for the walk of shame I was about to take out of the venue.

But as I started making my way out…

Something happened that changed everything.

A girl with tears in her eyes approached me to ask for a picture. 

She said something I said completely shifted her perspective on something she’d  been carrying for years. 

Minutes later, more people who waited after the event stopped me.
